    sourceNotes: `Key sources: Josephus, "Jewish War" (for the destruction of Jerusalem in AD 70); Tacitus, "Annals" 15.44 (for Nero's persecution); Pliny the Younger, "Letters" 10.96-97 (the earliest Roman administrative description of Christians, c. AD 112); Suetonius, "Lives of the Caesars" (for references to Christ/Chrestus and expulsion of Jews from Rome). Secondary sources: Meeks, Wayne, "The First Urban Christians: The Social World of the Apostle Paul" (1983, 2nd ed. 2003) — the foundational study of early Christian social history; Stark, Rodney, "The Rise of Christianity" (1996) — sociological analysis of church growth; Hurtado, Larry, "Destroyer of the Gods: Early Christian Distinctiveness in the Roman World" (2016); Jeffers, James, "The Greco-Roman World of the New Testament Era" (1999). For material culture and daily life: Stambaugh, John and Balch, David, "The New Testament in Its Social Environment" (1986); Osiek, Carolyn and Balch, David, "Families in the New Testament World" (1997). For women's roles: Torjesen, Karen Jo, "When Women Were Priests" (1993); Bauckham, Richard, "Gospel Women" (2002). Archaeological evidence: the Delphi Inscription (dating Gallio's proconsulship and thereby Paul's time in Corinth); the Erastus inscription at Corinth; excavations at Ephesus, Corinth, Philippi, and Rome. For the Roman economy and slavery: Finley, M.I., "The Ancient Economy" (1973); Glancy, Jennifer, "Slavery in Early Christianity" (2002). Acts of the Apostles and Paul's letters are the primary textual sources for the early church period.`,
